I can write about
one book a year.

00:32:05.670 --> 00:32:08.880
That's about the maximum,
because otherwise my brain

00:32:08.880 --> 00:32:09.470
will explode.

00:32:12.090 --> 00:32:13.060
What's your question?

00:32:13.060 --> 00:32:16.030
AUDIENCE: I'm a lost planet.

00:32:16.030 --> 00:32:17.212
RACHEL SEARLES: Are you?

00:32:17.212 --> 00:32:19.670
Silly.

00:32:19.670 --> 00:32:20.809
Back there, yes?

00:32:20.809 --> 00:32:22.392
AUDIENCE: Can you
tell us a little bit

00:32:22.392 --> 00:32:23.986
about your process
for writing books?

00:32:23.986 --> 00:32:25.315
How often you write, how long?

00:32:25.315 --> 00:32:26.190
RACHEL SEARLES: Sure.

00:32:26.190 --> 00:32:28.020
My process for
writing the books.

00:32:28.020 --> 00:32:31.730
On a daily basis, ideally, I
would write every single day.

00:32:31.730 --> 00:32:34.960
But that doesn't always happen
because life gets in the way.

00:32:34.960 --> 00:32:37.020
I prefer to write
in the morning.

00:32:37.020 --> 00:32:39.350
I don't usually
outline before I write.

00:32:39.350 --> 00:32:40.800
I tried to on the second book.

00:32:40.800 --> 00:32:42.510
I tried to plan
that whole book out,

00:32:42.510 --> 00:32:44.540
and I thought, oh, I'll
just have this road map

00:32:44.540 --> 00:32:46.706
I can follow, and I could
just write the whole thing

00:32:46.706 --> 00:32:48.340
in four weeks.

00:32:48.340 --> 00:32:50.080
And that didn't
work, because when

00:32:50.080 --> 00:32:51.890
I was trying to
outline it, I couldn't

00:32:51.890 --> 00:32:54.380
get past-- I don't know what's
going to happen in chapter

00:32:54.380 --> 00:32:56.463
four, because I haven't
written Chapter three yet.

00:32:56.463 --> 00:32:58.550
So I pretty much wing it.

00:32:58.550 --> 00:33:00.320
Maybe I have an idea
for the next chapter.

00:33:00.320 --> 00:33:04.570
I go chapter by
chapter, but it's slow.

00:33:04.570 --> 00:33:08.390
On good days, I still
try to 1,000 words a day.

00:33:08.390 --> 00:33:10.080
Yes?

00:33:10.080 --> 00:33:15.960
AUDIENCE: Similar to
those lines, [INAUDIBLE]

00:33:15.960 --> 00:33:17.430
do you remember
how many words it

00:33:17.430 --> 00:33:20.370
was by the time you started
it and by the time it actually

00:33:20.370 --> 00:33:21.990
shipped?

00:33:21.990 --> 00:33:23.490
RACHEL SEARLES:
Yeah, my word count.

00:33:23.490 --> 00:33:25.080
When I finished
that first draft,

00:33:25.080 --> 00:33:28.970
I really didn't have an idea
what age group I was writing

00:33:28.970 --> 00:33:31.750
for or, what the average
length of the book should be.

00:33:31.750 --> 00:33:34.115
So I just set this
random number in my head

00:33:34.115 --> 00:33:36.790
that I was going to write
a 100,000 word book.

00:33:36.790 --> 00:33:39.750
100,000 words is long
for a young adult book.

00:33:39.750 --> 00:33:42.850
For a middle grade
book, it's really long.

00:33:42.850 --> 00:33:47.470
So on my own, I trimmed it
down to about 70,000 words.

00:33:47.470 --> 00:33:49.519
About 70,000 when I was
sending it to agents.

00:33:49.519 --> 00:33:51.310
And by the time I was
sending it to agents,

00:33:51.310 --> 00:33:54.130
I had revised it
so much by myself,

00:33:54.130 --> 00:33:55.850
that when it sold
to the publisher

00:33:55.850 --> 00:33:59.260
we did one week of
revisions with my editor.

00:33:59.260 --> 00:34:00.220
Really light stuff.

00:34:00.220 --> 00:34:00.940
And sent it out.

00:34:00.940 --> 00:34:04.497
I think now it's between 70, 72.

00:34:04.497 --> 00:34:05.330
Something like that.

00:34:08.042 --> 00:34:08.900
No, thank you.

00:34:08.900 --> 00:34:09.399
Yes?

00:34:09.399 --> 00:34:11.199
AUDIENCE: How many
book have you made?

00:34:11.199 --> 00:34:12.210
RACHEL SEARLES: How
many books have I made?

00:34:12.210 --> 00:34:14.179
Well, this is the only
one I have out right now.

00:34:14.179 --> 00:34:16.220
And there's a second one
coming out next January.

00:34:18.969 --> 00:34:20.493
Yes?

00:34:20.493 --> 00:34:21.368
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:34:26.417 --> 00:34:28.500
RACHEL SEARLES: Do I have
lunch with other authors

00:34:28.500 --> 00:34:30.291
and talk about what
we're going to do next,

00:34:30.291 --> 00:34:33.110
and how we're going to
make our readers cry?

00:34:33.110 --> 00:34:34.580
There are a lot
of authors in LA,

00:34:34.580 --> 00:34:36.973
and I do have a lot of
friends who have books out.

00:34:36.973 --> 00:34:38.889
I'm going on a retreat
next weekend, actually,

00:34:38.889 --> 00:34:39.639
with some friends.

00:34:39.639 --> 00:34:42.010
We're going to-- we don't
talk about how we're

00:34:42.010 --> 00:34:45.159
going to torture our
readers, but we do talk.

00:34:45.159 --> 00:34:47.162
We help each other
out of potholes.

00:34:47.162 --> 00:34:48.870
Say if you're writing,
and you get stuck,

00:34:48.870 --> 00:34:50.060
and you don't know
what to do, and then

00:34:50.060 --> 00:34:51.429
you describe the
scene to your friends

00:34:51.429 --> 00:34:53.929
and they help you think of ways
to get back out of the hole.

00:34:56.120 --> 00:34:58.230
Yes?

00:34:58.230 --> 00:35:00.397
AUDIENCE: Are you thinking
about making a movie yet?

00:35:00.397 --> 00:35:02.813
RACHEL SEARLES: Am I thinking
about making a movie for it?

00:35:02.813 --> 00:35:04.260
That would be awesome.

00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:06.300
But we haven't sold
the movie rights.

00:35:06.300 --> 00:35:09.590
It's not up to me.

00:35:09.590 --> 00:35:10.333
Yes?

00:35:10.333 --> 00:35:11.208
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:35:17.315 --> 00:35:18.690
RACHEL SEARLES:
Yeah, maybe it'll

00:35:18.690 --> 00:35:19.815
be a cartoon movie someday.

00:35:19.815 --> 00:35:21.522
It would work well as a cartoon.

00:35:21.522 --> 00:35:22.397
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:35:31.465 --> 00:35:32.340
RACHEL SEARLES: Yeah.

00:35:32.340 --> 00:35:34.300
Some people change
their jobs all the time.

00:35:40.255 --> 00:35:40.755
Yes?

00:35:43.267 --> 00:35:45.850
AUDIENCE: Do you know if you're
going to make a movie of this?

00:35:45.850 --> 00:35:46.250
RACHEL SEARLES: Do
I know if anyone

00:35:46.250 --> 00:35:46.920
is going to make a movie?

00:35:46.920 --> 00:35:48.250
Somebody just asked that.

00:35:48.250 --> 00:35:50.616
So far, nobody's
going to make a movie.

00:35:50.616 --> 00:35:52.590
AUDIENCE: You should get one.

00:35:52.590 --> 00:35:54.830
RACHEL SEARLES:
I should get one?

00:35:54.830 --> 00:35:56.160
It would be nice.

00:35:56.160 --> 00:35:59.500
It's been submitted
to producers.

00:35:59.500 --> 00:36:00.000
Yes?

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:03.197
AUDIENCE: Do you plan
on going on a book tour?

00:36:03.197 --> 00:36:05.280
RACHEL SEARLES: Do I plan
on going on a book tour?

00:36:05.280 --> 00:36:07.220
When my book came out,
it came out January 28,

00:36:07.220 --> 00:36:10.020
and my publisher sent
me on a book tour.

00:36:10.020 --> 00:36:13.460
Just for a week to
schools around California.

00:36:13.460 --> 00:36:17.102
So now it's kind of--
you get your moment where

00:36:17.102 --> 00:36:18.810
the publisher pushes
you, and then you're

00:36:18.810 --> 00:36:19.510
kind of on your own.

00:36:19.510 --> 00:36:20.730
And you have to just
keep setting stuff up.

00:36:20.730 --> 00:36:23.540
So now I'm doing school visits
just on my own in the LA area.

00:36:26.980 --> 00:36:27.635
Anybody else?

00:36:30.510 --> 00:36:32.520
All right, are we all done here?

00:36:32.520 --> 00:36:33.325
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:36:33.325 --> 00:36:33.825
All

00:36:33.825 --> 00:36:35.090
RACHEL SEARLES: Right.

00:36:35.090 --> 00:36:37.420
OK, last question.

00:36:37.420 --> 00:36:37.920
What is it?

00:36:41.350 --> 00:36:44.220
AUDIENCE: Did you
get a lot of money?

00:36:44.220 --> 00:36:46.220
RACHEL SEARLES: [LAUGHS]
Did I get lots of money

00:36:46.220 --> 00:36:47.210
for making books?

00:36:47.210 --> 00:36:49.530
Writing books is an act of love.

00:36:49.530 --> 00:36:51.260
It's not a way to get rich.

00:36:51.260 --> 00:36:53.521
AUDIENCE: I'd like to get rich.

00:36:53.521 --> 00:36:55.520
RACHEL SEARLES: OK, thank
you so much for coming

00:36:55.520 --> 00:36:56.989
in and listening to me talk.

00:36:56.989 --> 00:36:58.030
I hope you like the book.

00:36:58.030 --> 00:37:01.080
[APPLAUSE]

